<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Marketing Writing Styles</title>

</head>

<body>
    <div class="grid">
        <div class="card">
            <div class="title">AIDA <span class="icon">üéØ</span></div>
            <div class="content">
                <p><strong>Attention, Interest, Desire, Action</strong></p>
                <p>A classic marketing model that guides customers through the buying process:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Attention: Grab the audience's attention with a compelling headline or opening.</li>
                    <li>Interest: Pique their interest with relevant information and benefits.</li>
                    <li>Desire: Create a strong desire for your product or service.</li>
                    <li>Action: Prompt the reader to take a specific action (e.g., buy, subscribe, learn more).</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Ideal for crafting persuasive ad copy, sales emails, and landing pages.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
            <div class="title">BAB <span class="icon">üîÑ</span></div>
            <div class="content">
                <p><strong>Before - After - Bridge</strong></p>
                <p>A framework that highlights the transformation your product or service offers:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Before: Describe the problem or current state.</li>
                    <li>After: Paint a picture of the ideal outcome.</li>
                    <li>Bridge: Explain how your offering bridges the gap between before and after.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Effective for case studies, product descriptions, and social media posts.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
            <div class="title">4 Cs <span class="icon">üß≠</span></div>
            <div class="content">
                <p><strong>Clear, Concise, Compelling, Credible</strong></p>
                <p>A guideline for creating effective marketing content:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Clear: Use simple language and avoid jargon.</li>
                    <li>Concise: Get to the point quickly and efficiently.</li>
                    <li>Compelling: Engage the reader with interesting and relevant information.</li>
                    <li>Credible: Back up claims with facts, statistics, or testimonials.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Applicable to all forms of marketing writing, from blog posts to press releases.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
            <div class="title">PAS <span class="icon">üÜò</span></div>
            <div class="content">
                <p><strong>Problem - Agitate - Solve</strong></p>
                <p>A persuasive writing formula that emphasizes the problem your product solves:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Problem: Identify a pain point or challenge your audience faces.</li>
                    <li>Agitate: Elaborate on the problem, stirring up emotions.</li>
                    <li>Solve: Present your product or service as the solution.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Particularly effective for sales pages, email marketing, and video scripts.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
            <div class="title">FAB <span class="icon">üíé</span></div>
            <div class="content">
                <p><strong>Features - Advantages - Benefits</strong></p>
                <p>A method for presenting product information in a customer-centric way:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Features: List the key characteristics of your product or service.</li>
                    <li>Advantages: Explain how these features give you an edge over competitors.</li>
                    <li>Benefits: Describe how these advantages improve the customer's life.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Useful for product descriptions, brochures, and sales presentations.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
            <div class="title">PASTOR <span class="icon">üôè</span></div>
            <div class="content">
                <p><strong>Person, Problem, Amplify, Story, Transformation, Offer, Response</strong></p>
                <p>A comprehensive framework for persuasive copywriting:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Person: Identify your target audience.</li>
                    <li>Problem: Address their main pain point.</li>
                    <li>Amplify: Emphasize the consequences of not solving the problem.</li>
                    <li>Story: Share a relatable narrative.</li>
                    <li>Transformation: Show how your solution changes lives.</li>
                    <li>Offer: Present your product or service.</li>
                    <li>Response: Call the reader to action.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Effective for long-form sales letters and video sales scripts.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
            <div class="title">QUEST <span class="icon">üó∫Ô∏è</span></div>
            <div class="content">
                <p><strong>Qualify, Understand, Educate, Stimulate, Transition</strong></p>
                <p>A content marketing approach focused on guiding the customer journey:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Qualify: Ensure you're targeting the right audience.</li>
                    <li>Understand: Demonstrate that you comprehend their needs.</li>
                    <li>Educate: Provide valuable information and insights.</li>
                    <li>Stimulate: Encourage engagement and interaction.</li>
                    <li>Transition: Guide them towards making a purchase decision.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Ideal for creating content marketing strategies and nurturing campaigns.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
            <div class="title">PPPP <span class="icon">üìä</span></div>
            <div class="content">
                <p><strong>Picture, Promise, Prove, Push</strong></p>
                <p>A framework for creating persuasive marketing messages:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Picture: Paint a vivid image of the desired outcome.</li>
                    <li>Promise: Make a clear promise of what your product/service will deliver.</li>
                    <li>Prove: Provide evidence to support your claims (testimonials, data, etc.).</li>
                    <li>Push: Encourage the reader to take immediate action.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Effective for crafting compelling advertisements and sales pages.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
            <div class="title">4 U's <span class="icon">üé®</span></div>
            <div class="content">
                <p><strong>Useful, Urgent, Unique, Ultra-specific</strong></p>
                <p>A guideline for creating attention-grabbing headlines and content:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Useful: Offer practical value to the reader.</li>
                    <li>Urgent: Create a sense of timeliness or immediacy.</li>
                    <li>Unique: Present information in a fresh, distinctive way.</li>
                    <li>Ultra-specific: Use concrete details to increase credibility and relevance.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Particularly valuable for crafting email subject lines and blog post titles.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
            <div class="title">STAR <span class="icon">‚≠ê</span></div>
            <div class="content">
                <p><strong>Story, Task, Action, Result</strong></p>
                <p>A storytelling framework often used in case studies and testimonials:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Story: Set the scene and introduce the characters (clients).</li>
                    <li>Task: Describe the challenge or goal they faced.</li>
                    <li>Action: Explain how your product/service was implemented.</li>
                    <li>Result: Highlight the positive outcomes and benefits achieved.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Effective for showcasing real-world applications and success stories.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</body>

